<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-413-848  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 413 848.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  April 18 1990 n1504 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Contrast: technology and poverty.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bennett, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The contrast between the high technology in which a few Indiancitizens work and the low technology in which the vast majoritymust live is greatest in the software business, not only in termsof India's largely peasant population but in terms of its softwareexpertise, some of the finest in the world.andP;  A task force hasestablished seven areas that are key to making Indian software aworld player: manpower; the domestic market; the export market;finance; politics; infrastructure; and software piracy.andP;  Themanpower problem is essentially a brain drain issue; it isestimated that 58 percent of graduates from electronics andcomputer courses emigrate from India.andP;  The issue for the domesticmarket is integration of computers into the country, a difficulttask when hardware is being sold at as much as ten times the goingrate.andP;  The other areas highlighted by the task force are alsoexplored.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TechnologyDeveloping CountriesIndiaSoftwareBrain Drain.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>